# Force LF line endings on files that have to be interpreted by a Unix
# shell, regardless of git's autocrlf setting on the client. Without
# this, a Windows clone with `core.autocrlf=true` (the default) gets
# CRLF endings on `scripts/bootstrap.sh`, turning the
# `#!/usr/bin/env bash` shebang into `env bash\r`, which the kernel
# then can't resolve → `bash\r: No such file or directory`.
#
# Other text files (.md, .json, source code) are left to git's default
# normalization — most editors handle either ending fine, and we don't
# want to fight people's local editor settings on prose.
*.sh   text eol=lf
*.bash text eol=lf
# `scripts/bootstrap.sh`, `scripts/install.sh` and friends without a
# .sh suffix get the same treatment when added later. The leading
# `scripts/` keeps the rule scoped — we don't want eol=lf on, say, a
# Windows-only helper that ends up in this dir by mistake.
scripts/*.sh text eol=lf

# Conversely, PowerShell scripts should stay CRLF — that's what Windows
# tooling (and pwsh on Windows) writes by default. Forcing CRLF
# explicitly prevents a *nix contributor's editor from quietly rewriting
# them to LF, which trips up some older PS hosts.
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
